Aim: To write a java program that import and use the user defined packages.
Description:
 In Java, user-defined packages allow you to group related classes and interfaces together, making
your code more modular, organized, and easier to manage. A package is essentially a namespace
that organizes classes and interfaces in a way that avoids naming conflicts and enhances code
maintainability.
How to Create and Use User-Defined Packages:
1. Creating a Package: To create a user-defined package, you use the package keyword at the top of
your Java source file. This defines the package name. package packagename;
2. Using the Package: To use the classes from a user-defined package, you need to import the
package in the class where you want to use it, using the import statement.
1) import pacakgename.*;// importing all classes and interfaces except sub packages
2) import packagename.classname; //importing specified class in that package
3) packagename.classname obj=new packagename.classname() //fully qualified importing
for different packeges have same classname to avoid collision.

Source code:
Package Code:
package pack1;
public class Addition {
public void add(int a, int b) {
int c = a + b;
System.out.println("The sum is " + c);
}
}
Program Code:
import pack1.Addition;
class demopack {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Addition a1 = new Addition();
a1.add(15, 27);
}
}
How to Compile:
Save these Code snippets in two Separate files named as
Addition.java & demopack.java.
Use the following commands to compile and run


